  "prompt": "Japanese Etiquette, Behavior, and Habits: How does tipping work in Japan?",
  "response": "In Japan, tipping is not a customary practice and can actually be considered rude or awkward. Here are the key points about tipping in Japan:\n\n1. No Tipping Culture\n- Tipping is not expected in any service industry\n- Service workers are paid fair wages and take pride in providing excellent service\n- Leaving a tip can be seen as insulting or confusing\n\n2. Restaurants\n- No tipping at restaurants, cafes, or bars\n- Service charges are often already included in the bill\n- Good service is considered a standard expectation, not something requiring extra payment\n\n3. Taxi Services\n- No tipping for taxi drivers\n- The fare is the exact amount to be paid\n- Drivers are professional and provide courteous service without expecting extra money\n\n4. Hotels\n- No tipping for bellhops, housekeeping, or concierge\n- High-end hotels might have a service charge included in the bill\n- Exceptional service is appreciated through politeness and gratitude\n\n5. Rare Exceptions\n- Some high-end international hotels or tourist areas might be more familiar with tipping\n- In these cases, a small tip might be accepted, but it's still not expected\n\nThe best approach is to simply say \"thank you\" and be respectful when receiving service in Japan.",
